            <p class="base-aside-card__subtitle font-sans text-sm text-color-text leading-regular break-words overflow-anywhere
                line-clamp-2">
              
          💻 Daily Dose of Data Structures – Day 13
🟥⚫ "Red-Black Tree – Balanced BST with a Twist of Color!"
Yesterday we explored AVL Trees that keep things balanced using height and rotations.
Today, meet another self-balancing BST — the Red-Black Tree.

🧠 What is a Red-Black Tree?
A Red-Black Tree is a type of self-balancing Binary Search Tree where each node has an extra color attribute: either Red or Black.

It uses coloring rules and rotations to keep the tree approximately balanced.

⚖️ Key Red-Black Tree Properties
Every node is either Red or Black.

The root is always Black.

No two Red nodes can be adjacent (no Red-Red parent-child).

Every path from a node to a null child has the same number of Black nodes.

New nodes are inserted as Red, and tree is adjusted via rotations &amp; recoloring.

🔁 Rotations
Just like AVL Trees, Red-Black Trees use Left and Right Rotations to fix balance after insertions/deletions.

But unlike AVL, it prioritizes fewer rotations over being perfectly balanced.

📊 Time Complexities
Operation	Time Complexity
Search	O(log n)
Insert	O(log n)
Delete	O(log n)

Slightly slower than AVL in practice, but less rotation-heavy, making it great for large datasets (used in Java TreeMap, TreeSet).

🧠 Real-World Use
Red-Black Trees are used in Java Collections Framework, Linux kernel, and C++ STL (map, set) due to their performance and efficiency.

#java #Tree #bst #linkedin
        
            </p>

