            <p class="base-aside-card__subtitle font-sans text-sm text-color-text leading-regular break-words overflow-anywhere
                line-clamp-2">
              
          🚀 DSA Journey – Day 9 | Climbing Stairs (Dynamic Programming)
Today, I solved the classic Climbing Stairs problem, which is a great introduction to Dynamic Programming.
🔹 Problem Statement:
 You are climbing a staircase with n steps.
 At each step, you can climb either 1 step or 2 steps.
 Find the number of distinct ways to reach the top.
🔹 Key Insight:
 To reach step n, you can only come from:
Step n - 1
Step n - 2
So the recurrence becomes:

ways(n) = ways(n - 1) + ways(n - 2)
This follows the Fibonacci pattern.
🔹 Approach Used:
 ✅ Dynamic Programming
 ✅ Bottom-up calculation
 ✅ Optimized to constant space
🔹 Why this problem matters?
Builds strong DP fundamentals
Frequently asked in interviews
Helps understand overlapping subproblems
📌 Learning step by step, building logic one problem at a time.
#DSA #Day9 #DynamicProgramming #Java #ProblemSolving #LearningInPublic #InterviewPreparation #CodingJourney #LeetCode
        
            </p>

